 The frequency of earth movements prompts Chileans to say that every president has at least one major earthquake during the traditional six-year term in office.
 The long history of earth movements in Chile has led to a sharing of information with U.S. and Japanese scientists and engineers over the behavior of the earth and of buildings during earthquakes.
 Since earthquake building codes were implemented in Chile in the 1930s, only two engineered buildings have collapsed, he said.
 Descriptions of earthquakes in Chile date back to Spanish settlers in 1575.
 Parts of the coast stretching south from the city of Concepcion, 325 miles south of Santiago, dropped nine feet. "It was the biggest registered in the history of seismic instrumention," said Kausel.
